Author-Name:    Pesendorfer, Wolfgang
Title:   Design Innovation and Fashion Cycles. 
Journal: American Economic Review
Pages: 771-92
Issue: 4
Volume: 85
Year: 1995
Month:  September 
Abstract:
  A model of fashion cycles is developed in which designs are used as a
 signaling device in a 'dating game.' A monopolist periodically creates a
 new design. Over time the price of the design falls as it spreads across
 the population. Once sufficiently many consumers own the design it is
 profitable to create a new design and thereby render the old design
 obsolete. This paper gives conditions under which all consumers would be
 better-off by banning the use of fashion. Competition among designers may
 lead to less frequent changes in fashion and to higher prices than
 monopoly.   Copyright 1995 by American Economic Association.
