Template-Type: ReDIF-Article 1.0
Author-Name:    Metrick, Andrew
Title:   A Natural Experiment in "Jeopardy!". 
Journal: American Economic Review
Pages: 240-53
Issue: 1
Volume: 85
Year: 1995
Month:  March 
Abstract:
  This paper uses the television game show 'Jeopardy!' as a natural
 experiment to analyze behavior under uncertainty and the ability of
 players to choose strategic best-responses. The results suggest that,
 while most players bet in a rational manner, the failure rate for choosing
 best-responses increases as the betting problem grows more complex and
 that players' choices are affected by the 'frame' of the problem. However,
 suboptimal betting tends to decrease as inferior players are driven from
 the game. The data also allow for estimation of the extent of risk
 aversion; the results imply near risk-neutrality.   Copyright 1995 by American Economic Association.
