Author-Name:    Coate, Stephen
Title:   Altruism, the Samaritan's Dilemma, and Government Transfer Policy. 
Journal: American Economic Review
Pages: 46-57
Issue: 1
Volume: 85
Year: 1995
Month:  March 
Abstract:
  This paper shows that altruism provides an efficiency rationale for
 public provision of insurance to the poor. The framework is one in which
 there are rich altruists and risk-averse poor who face some possibility of
 loss. The government represents the rich and makes transfers on their
 behalf. With unconditional transfers, the poor may forgo insurance and
 rely on private charity to bail them out in the event of loss. This
 reliance on private charity has adverse efficiency effects. These may be
 avoided if the government makes in-kind transfers of insurance.   Copyright 1995 by American Economic Association.
