Author-Name:    Borjas, George J
Title:   Ethnicity, Neighborhoods, and Human-Capital Externalities. 
Journal: American Economic Review
Pages: 365-90
Issue: 3
Volume: 85
Year: 1995
Month:  June 
Abstract:
  The socioeconomic performance of today's workers depends not only on
 parental skills but also on the average skills of the ethnic group in the
 parents' generation (or ethnic capital). This paper investigates the link
 between the ethnic externality and ethnic neighborhoods. The evidence
 indicates that residential segregation and the external effect of
 ethnicity are linked, partly because ethnic capital summarizes the
 socioeconomic background of the neighborhood where the children were
 raised. Ethnicity has an external effect, even among persons who grow up
 in the same neighborhood, when children are exposed frequently to persons
 who share the same ethnic background.	 Copyright 1995 by American Economic Association.
